5000|$|In 1976, Vanunu {{applied for}} {{a job at the}} Negev Nuclear Research Center, an Israeli {{facility}} used to <b>develop</b> and manufacture <b>nuclear</b> <b>weapons</b> located in the Negev Desert south of Dimona. Most worldwide intelligence agencies estimate that Israel <b>developed</b> <b>nuclear</b> <b>weapons</b> as early as the 1960s, but the country has intentionally maintained a [...] "nuclear ambiguity", neither acknowledging nor denying that it possesses <b>nuclear</b> <b>weapons.</b> Vanunu was responding to an advertisement for trainee technicians to work at the facility.|$|R
50|$|In 2009, a U.S. poll {{conducted}} Sep. 30 to Oct. 1 by the Pew Research Center, found 61% agreed {{it was more}} important to prevent Iran from <b>developing</b> <b>nuclear</b> <b>weapons,</b> even if it means taking military action.|$|R
